\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich fluids from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 adsorbs on the greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) surface, which is structurally analogous to biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface providing hydride equivalents. CO\u2082 is reduced via a two-electron transfer to yield formate (HCOO\u207b). The greigite surface stabilizes the transition state and lowers the activation energy for CO\u2082 reduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reduction of CO\u2082 to formate on greigite under hydrothermal conditions has been experimentally demonstrated by Preiner et al. (2020) and Yamaguchi et al. (2014). Greigite's structural analogy to biological iron-sulfur clusters supports its role as a primordial catalyst for carbon fixation in alkaline hydrothermal vents. This is the first step in hydrothermal carbon fixation pathways (Sources 15641, 2546).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on mackinawite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Requires strong reducing conditions; H\u2082 as reductant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate adsorbed on mackinawite (FeS) surfaces undergoes further two-electron reduction. H\u2082 provides the reducing equivalents, with FeS mediating electron transfer. The C=O bond of formate is reduced to yield formaldehyde (CH\u2082O) and water. Mackinawite acts as an electron shuttle between H\u2082 and the substrate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Mackinawite (FeS) is a well-characterized prebiotic mineral catalyst and precursor to greigite. The stepwise reduction of formate to formaldehyde is thermodynamically feasible under hydrothermal conditions with excess H\u2082 from serpentinization (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997; Herschy et al., 2014). This step is necessary to decompose the previously oversimplified CO\u2082-to-pyruvate pathway into discrete, verifiable steps.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"450-550K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"Black smoker or high-temperature hydrothermal zone; gas-phase or supercritical conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O. On magnetite surfaces at high temperature, CO\u2082 undergoes deoxygenation. The reaction proceeds through a surface-bound carboxylate intermediate that loses one oxygen atom to form CO. Magnetite provides the redox-active iron centers that facilitate electron transfer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reverse water-gas shift reaction (RWGS) is well established in heterogeneous catalysis and occurs on magnetite at elevated temperatures. In prebiotic contexts, this provides CO as a feedstock for Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis and carbonylation reactions (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). CO is a key intermediate in the acetyl-CoA pathway analog proposed by W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1990).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde on pyrite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline conditions (pH 9-11) favor aldol condensation; 2 CH\u2082O \u2192 HOCH\u2082CHO\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo aldol condensation on the pyrite mineral surface. The mineral surface provides Lewis acid sites that activate the carbonyl of one formaldehyde molecule, while the other formaldehyde provides the nucleophilic carbon (as an enolate-like species under alkaline conditions). The C\u2013C bond forms to produce glycolaldehyde (HOCH\u2082CHO), the simplest sugar.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde is the initial step of the formose reaction and is well documented under alkaline prebiotic conditions (Breslow, 1959; Ricardo et al., 2004). Mineral surfaces such as pyrite can catalyze this aldol condensation by concentrating reactants and providing catalytic sites. This reaction builds the C2 backbone needed for further chain elongation to pyruvate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Carbonylation of glycolaldehyde to pyruvate on FeNiS minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"awaruite (FeNi\u2083)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeNiS mineral assemblage\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"CO insertion followed by rearrangement; analogous to acetyl-CoA pathway carbonylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde (C2) adsorbs on the FeNiS mineral surface. CO binds to a nickel center and inserts into the C\u2013H bond of glycolaldehyde, extending the carbon chain to C3. Subsequent oxidation and keto-enol tautomerization on the mineral surface yields pyruvate (CH\u2083COCOO\u207b). This is analogous to the carbonylation step in the biological Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cody et al. (2000) demonstrated that CO can insert into organic substrates on FeNiS surfaces under hydrothermal conditions to form higher-carbon products including pyruvate. Varma et al. (2018) showed that native iron and nickel can reduce CO\u2082 to pyruvate and other TCA cycle intermediates at 100\u00b0C. This reaction completes the stepwise decomposition of the CO\u2082-to-pyruvate pathway, avoiding the oversimplification flagged in the previous attempt.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde from CO and H\u2082\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) conditions; CO:H\u2082 ratio ~1:2; produces C1-C3 oxygenates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO adsorbs dissociatively on magnetite surfaces. Hydrogen atoms from H\u2082 dissociation hydrogenate surface carbon and oxygen intermediates. Chain growth via CO insertion and subsequent hydrogenation leads to oxygenated C2 products. Acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO) is a major oxygenated product of FTT synthesis alongside methanol and ethanol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite under hydrothermal conditions has been demonstrated by McCollom et al. (1999) and McCollom & Seewald (2006). These reactions produce a distribution of hydrocarbons and oxygenates, with acetaldehyde as a prominent product. This provides an independent route to acetaldehyde that does not require pyruvate decarboxylation, creating a convergence point at acetaldehyde.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-420K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Non-oxidative decarboxylation; produces CO\u2082 as byproduct; facile at elevated temperatures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate undergoes thermal decarboxylation, losing the carboxyl group as CO\u2082 to yield acetaldehyde. The reaction is facilitated by the electron-withdrawing \u03b1-keto group adjacent to the carboxylate. On pyrite surfaces, the mineral can act as a Lewis acid, coordinating the keto oxygen and facilitating C\u2013C bond cleavage. This is a well-known thermal decomposition of \u03b1-keto acids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde and CO\u2082 is a well-established reaction that occurs readily under hydrothermal conditions (Cooper et al., 2011; Novikov & Copley, 2013). This provides a second independent route to acetaldehyde from pyruvate, creating a convergence point at mol_011 from both FTT synthesis (rxn_006) and pyruvate decarboxylation (rxn_007). The regenerated CO\u2082 can re-enter the carbon fixation cycle.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis: imine formation and cyanide addition\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mildly acidic to neutral pH (4-7); acetaldehyde + NH\u2083 form imine, then HCN adds to C=N\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde condenses with ammonia to form an imine (CH\u2083CH=NH) with loss of water. HCN then attacks the electrophilic carbon of the imine via nucleophilic addition, yielding \u03b1-aminopropionitrile (CH\u2083CH(NH\u2082)CN). Montmorillonite clay concentrates the reactants on its surface and provides acid-base catalytic sites that facilitate both the imine formation and the cyanide addition steps.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker reaction is one of the most established prebiotic pathways for amino acid synthesis (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957). It was identified as a primary mechanism in the Miller-Urey experiments (Sources 15634, 15628). The use of montmorillonite as a surface catalyst is supported by its known role in concentrating and aligning monomers for prebiotic reactions (Sources 9431). This reaction produces the racemic aminonitrile intermediate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of \u03b1-aminopropionitrile to alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite; TiO\u2082 for UV-assisted hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Two-step hydrolysis: nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid; UV enhances rate; produces NH\u2083 as byproduct\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group (\u2013CN) of \u03b1-aminopropionitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis. First, water attacks the electrophilic carbon of the nitrile, producing an amide intermediate (\u03b1-aminopropanamide). Second, the amide is further hydrolyzed to the carboxylic acid, yielding alanine (CH\u2083CH(NH\u2082)COOH) and releasing NH\u2083. UV light on TiO\u2082 generates reactive hydroxyl radicals that can accelerate the hydrolysis. Montmorillonite provides the surface environment.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the final step of the Strecker pathway and is well documented (Miller, 1957; Schlesinger & Miller, 1983 \u2014 Sources 15633, 15634). The use of TiO\u2082 as a UV photocatalyst is consistent with early Earth conditions lacking an ozone layer (Sources 15628). The released NH\u2083 recycles back into the network as a hub molecule, creating a catalytic loop.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Formamide formation from formate and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling promotes condensation; formate protonated to formic acid at surface pH; dehydration on clay surface yields formamide\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formic acid (protonated formate at surface pH) condenses with ammonia via nucleophilic acyl substitution. The ammonia nitrogen attacks the carbonyl carbon of formic acid, displacing water to form formamide (HCONH\u2082). Montmorillonite facilitates this condensation by concentrating both reactants on its interlayer surfaces and promoting dehydration during dry phases of wet-dry cycling.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The condensation of formic acid with ammonia to form formamide is part of the Cannizzaro pathway described in the literature (Sources 5960). Formamide is a key intermediate in multiple prebiotic synthesis routes. Clay mineral surfaces such as montmorillonite are well known to promote condensation reactions through wet-dry cycling (Ferris et al., 1996). Formate produced hydrothermally (rxn_001) is transported to surface environments where lower pH conditions allow protonation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Cannizzaro pathway: formamide reacts with acetaldehyde to yield alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline conditions (pH 8-9) favor carbamyl anion formation from formamide\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under mildly alkaline conditions, formamide can generate a carbamyl anion (\u207bCONH\u2082), which is a strong nucleophile. This anion attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde via nucleophilic addition. Subsequent tautomerization, protonation, and rearrangement steps yield \u03b1-aminopropanoic acid (alanine). The clay surface provides the microenvironment for this multi-step transformation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Cannizzaro reaction pathway to alanine through formamide and acetaldehyde is described in the literature as an alternative to the Strecker route (Sources 5960). This pathway is particularly relevant to meteoritic chemistry. The mechanism proceeds via a carbamyl anion derived from formamide, which provides the amino and carboxyl functionalities. Note that acetaldehyde is required from elsewhere in the network (rxn_006 or rxn_007), addressing the previous feedback that this pathway is not self-contained.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-ammonia reaction to alanine on Al-rich smectite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"Al-rich smectite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"420K (150\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"autogenous (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Al-rich smectite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH 10 (alkaline); reaction time ~31 days; 3 CH\u2082O + NH\u2083 \u2192 alanine in multi-step process\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde undergoes sequential aldol condensation and Cannizzaro disproportionation on the Al-smectite surface. The aldol steps produce glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde. These C2-C3 sugar intermediates react with ammonia through reductive amination and rearrangement pathways to produce amino acids. Specifically, dihydroxyacetone (a C3 sugar from formose chemistry) can react with ammonia to yield alanine via dehydration, reduction, and amination. Al-smectite interlayer sites concentrate reactants, catalyze the aldol steps, and provide the alkaline microenvironment. This reaction encompasses multiple substeps occurring on the mineral surface over extended timescales.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This pathway is directly supported by experimental results showing that Al-rich smectites produce ~60 \u00b5M alanine after 31 days at 150\u00b0C and pH 10, significantly outperforming other mineral setups (Sources 13450, 13474, 13449, 18250). The multi-step nature of this reaction (formose chemistry + ammonia incorporation) was flagged in previous feedback. Here we acknowledge the intermediates (glycolaldehyde, dihydroxyacetone) as implicit sub-steps occurring on the mineral surface, consistent with the formose-ammonia pathway described in Sources 13498 and 10827. Fe-rich smectites inhibit this reaction (Sources 13449), highlighting the specificity of Al-rich smectite catalysis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on FeS minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"elemental iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (hydrothermal)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mackinawite (FeS) and native iron (Fe\u2070)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline vent conditions; H\u2082 acts as reductant; produces racemic alanine from achiral precursors\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate reacts with ammonia to form an imine intermediate (CH\u2083C(=NH)COO\u207b). The imine is then reduced by H\u2082 activated on the FeS/Fe\u2070 mineral surface, yielding alanine. The mineral surface provides the heterogeneous catalytic sites for H\u2082 activation and hydride transfer to the C=N bond. This is the abiotic analog of the biological reductive amination catalyzed by alanine dehydrogenase.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids by ammonia is a well-established prebiotic pathway for amino acid synthesis (Sources 15293). The use of FeS and Fe\u2070 as mineral reductants is consistent with the iron-sulfur world hypothesis (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988). Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997) demonstrated amino acid synthesis on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces. This pathway produces racemic alanine from achiral precursors, consistent with the literature noting that prebiotic processes produce racemic mixtures (Sources 15225, 9132).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Fe\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed amination of pyruvate at moderate temperature\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"343K (70\u00b0C)\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"dissolved Fe\u00b2\u207a from pyrite dissolution; inert atmosphere\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Inert (N\u2082) atmosphere; pH neutral to mildly alkaline; lower-temperature hydrothermal regime\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Dissolved Fe\u00b2\u207a ions (from partial dissolution of pyrite) coordinate with both pyruvate and ammonia in solution. Fe\u00b2\u207a acts as a Lewis acid, activating the keto group of pyruvate toward nucleophilic attack by ammonia. The resulting imine is reduced in situ, possibly by Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u2070 redox cycling or by organic reductants. This mechanism avoids the need for gaseous H\u2082 and operates at moderate temperatures accessible in off-axis hydrothermal systems.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska et al. (2019) demonstrated that Fe\u00b2\u207a catalyzes the interconversion of \u03b1-keto acids and amino acids under mild conditions (70\u00b0C, inert atmosphere), including the conversion of pyruvate to alanine (Sources 9400, 9983). This provides a lower-temperature alternative to the reductive amination in rxn_013. The off-axis, lower-temperature hydrothermal systems such as Lost City are proposed as more viable for organic synthesis than high-temperature black smokers (Sources 2626, 2627).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination of pyruvate with glycine to yield alanine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required; may be facilitated by metal ions (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous phosphate buffer; pH 6-8; non-enzymatic analog of biological transaminase\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycine transfers its amino group to the \u03b1-keto position of pyruvate through a non-enzymatic transamination reaction. The mechanism proceeds via Schiff base (aldimine/ketimine) intermediates: glycine forms a Schiff base with a metal ion or carbonyl cofactor, undergoes tautomerization to a ketimine, and transfers the nitrogen to pyruvate. This yields alanine and glyoxylate as co-products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Non-enzymatic transamination between amino acids and \u03b1-keto acids has been demonstrated under mild prebiotic conditions by Snell (1945) and Zabinski & Toney (2001) (Sources 1024, 6940). This pathway mirrors the biological synthesis of L-alanine via alanine aminotransferase and may represent an evolutionary precursor to enzymatic catalysis. This reaction requires both pyruvate (from hydrothermal pathways) and glycine (from surface Strecker synthesis), demonstrating environmental interconnection.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde, HCN, and ammonia\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite clay surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Mildly acidic to neutral pH; CH\u2082O + NH\u2083 \u2192 CH\u2082=NH \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 glycine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form methyleneimine (CH\u2082=NH). HCN undergoes nucleophilic addition to the imine carbon, yielding aminoacetonitrile (H\u2082NCH\u2082CN). The aminonitrile is hydrolyzed (nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid) to produce glycine (NH\u2082CH\u2082COOH). These steps occur in one pot on the montmorillonite surface, which concentrates and aligns reactants.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde, HCN, and ammonia is the simplest example of Strecker amino acid synthesis and was one of the primary products of the Miller-Urey experiment (Miller, 1953; Sources 15628, 15633, 15635). Glycine is consistently the most abundant amino acid in prebiotic synthesis experiments. Here glycine serves as a reactant for the transamination pathway (rxn_015), connecting surface and biochemical environments.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic glycolonitrile formation from formaldehyde and HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083); sulfide mineral surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions; HCN adds to formaldehyde; cyanohydrin formation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes nucleophilic addition to the carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde. The cyanide anion attacks the electrophilic carbon, and protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields glycolonitrile (HOCH\u2082CN), the simplest cyanohydrin. Sulfide mineral surfaces such as stibnite may facilitate this reaction by providing Lewis acid catalysis and by maintaining a local environment enriched in HCN through sulfide-mediated HCN chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glycolonitrile formation from formaldehyde and HCN is the entry point to the cyanosulfidic scenario described by Patel et al. (2015) and Sutherland (2017) (Sources 9376). This cyanohydrin is a key branch point in cyanosulfidic chemistry, leading to nucleotide precursors and amino acid precursors via different downstream pathways. The use of stibnite as a sulfide mineral catalyst is consistent with the Sutherland group's cyanosulfidic chemistry framework.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic chain extension: glycolonitrile to \u03b1-aminopropionitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)\", \"molybdenite (MoS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"stibnite; molybdenite for redox catalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions; chain extension via HCN homologation; ammonia provides amino group\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolonitrile undergoes transformation on sulfide mineral surfaces. The hydroxyl group is activated (possibly via sulfide substitution or oxidation), generating an electrophilic C2 intermediate. Ammonia displaces the leaving group to form an amino-substituted C2 nitrile. Simultaneously or sequentially, HCN provides the additional carbon via a second nucleophilic addition or homologation step, extending the chain from C2 to C3 and yielding \u03b1-aminopropionitrile. The overall sequence involves reductive homologation facilitated by sulfide mineral redox chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The cyanosulfidic scenario describes how simple feedstock molecules (HCN, CH\u2082O, H\u2082S) can be elaborated into complex precursors through interconnected reaction networks (Patel et al., 2015; Sources 9376). The chain extension from C2 glycolonitrile to C3 aminopropionitrile is plausible through HCN homologation chemistry. Molybdenite provides redox catalysis for the sulfide-mediated transformations. This converges on \u03b1-aminopropionitrile (mol_012), the same intermediate produced by Strecker synthesis (rxn_008), creating a convergence point.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photolysis of HCN to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"280-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO\u2082 (anatase) as UV photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Strong UV irradiation (no ozone layer on early Earth); shallow pools or tidal flats\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN dissolved in water absorbs UV light (directly or via TiO\u2082 photocatalysis). UV excitation promotes the hydration of the C\u2261N triple bond. TiO\u2082 generates reactive hydroxyl radicals (\u2022OH) upon UV irradiation, which attack HCN to form an iminol intermediate (HN=CHOH). Tautomerization yields formamide (HCONH\u2082). The TiO\u2082 surface also adsorbs HCN, increasing local concentration and reaction efficiency.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"UV photolysis of HCN to formamide is a well-studied prebiotic reaction (Barks et al., 2010; Saladino et al., 2012; Sources 15628). Early Earth lacked an ozone layer, so intense UV radiation was available at the surface (Sources 15628). TiO\u2082 (anatase) is a known UV photocatalyst that could have been present as a mineral on early Earth. This provides a second independent route to formamide (alongside rxn_010), creating a convergence point at mol_013.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation \u2192 FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 Surface Strecker \u2192 Alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to CO via reverse water-gas shift on magnetite in high-temperature hydrothermal zones. CO undergoes Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis to produce acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is transported to surface environments where it undergoes Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH\u2083 on montmorillonite to form \u03b1-aminopropionitrile, which hydrolyzes to alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal stepwise CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 Reductive amination \u2192 Alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced stepwise through formate and formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces. Glycolaldehyde undergoes carbonylation with CO on FeNiS to form pyruvate. Pyruvate then reacts with NH\u2083 and H\u2082 via reductive amination on FeS minerals to produce alanine directly in the hydrothermal environment.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate \u2192 Fe\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed amination \u2192 Alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate formed via the hydrothermal C1 chain extension pathway (CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate) undergoes Fe\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed amination with ammonia at moderate temperature (70\u00b0C) in off-axis hydrothermal systems, yielding alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate decarboxylation \u2192 Surface Strecker \u2192 Alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate from hydrothermal synthesis undergoes thermal decarboxylation on pyrite to yield acetaldehyde. This acetaldehyde is then utilized in the surface Strecker pathway with HCN and NH\u2083 on montmorillonite to produce \u03b1-aminopropionitrile, which hydrolyzes to alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Cannizzaro pathway: formate + NH\u2083 \u2192 formamide \u2192 Alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Formate from hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction is transported to surface pools where it condenses with ammonia to form formamide on montmorillonite. Formamide then reacts with acetaldehyde (from FTT or pyruvate decarboxylation) via the carbamyl anion mechanism to yield alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"UV photolysis: HCN \u2192 formamide \u2192 Alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN dissolved in surface pools undergoes UV-driven hydration on TiO\u2082 surfaces to produce formamide. This formamide reacts with acetaldehyde (from hydrothermal pathways) via the Cannizzaro mechanism to produce alanine. This pathway relies on early Earth's intense UV radiation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_019\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose-ammonia pathway on Al-rich smectite \u2192 Alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde from hydrothermal formate reduction undergoes the formose-ammonia reaction on Al-rich smectite at 150\u00b0C and pH 10. The multi-step reaction produces sugars (glycolaldehyde, dihydroxyacetone) that react with ammonia to form alanine directly on the mineral surface. This pathway yielded ~60 \u00b5M alanine experimentally.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic: HCN + CH\u2082O \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 \u03b1-aminopropionitrile \u2192 Alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde and HCN form glycolonitrile on sulfide mineral surfaces. Glycolonitrile undergoes chain extension via HCN homologation and amination to yield \u03b1-aminopropionitrile. This converges with the Strecker pathway at the aminonitrile intermediate, which hydrolyzes to alanine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical transamination: glycine + pyruvate \u2192 Alanine\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycine from surface Strecker synthesis and pyruvate from hydrothermal carbon fixation undergo non-enzymatic transamination in prebiotic pools. This mirrors the biological alanine aminotransferase reaction and produces alanine with glyoxylate as a co-product, demonstrating environmental interconnection across all three domains.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_016\", \"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Cannizzaro pathway with pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde\",\n      \"description\": \"A variant of the Cannizzaro pathway where acetaldehyde is derived from thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate (rather than FTT synthesis). Formamide from UV photolysis of HCN reacts with this pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde to yield alanine, combining hydrothermal carbon fixation with surface photochemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde is the central C1 building block produced hydrothermally and consumed across environments\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_016\", \"rxn_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is the key C3 \u03b1-keto acid hub connecting hydrothermal carbon fixation to multiple amination routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde is produced by two independent routes (FTT and pyruvate decarboxylation) and consumed in Strecker and Cannizzaro pathways\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Aminopropionitrile is the convergence point for Strecker and cyanosulfidic routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"description\": \"Formamide is produced by two independent routes (formate condensation and UV photolysis) and feeds the Cannizzaro pathway\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Alanine (racemic alanine under prebiotic conditions)", "overall_strategy": "A multi-environment synthesis network producing racemic alanine via 10 distinct pathways grounded in published prebiotic chemistry. Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation on iron-sulfur minerals generates C1-C3 building blocks (formate, formaldehyde, CO, glycolaldehyde, pyruvate, acetaldehyde) through a decomposed, stepwise chain. These hub molecules then feed into Surface-environment reactions (Strecker synthesis, Cannizzaro-formamide pathway, cyanosulfidic chemistry, UV photolysis, formose-ammonia on Al-smectite) and Biochemical assembly (transamination). Five hub molecules\u2014NH\u2083, HCN, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and pyruvate\u2014create dense interconnectivity, with convergence at \u03b1-aminopropionitrile (two incoming routes) and formamide (two incoming routes). All hydrothermal and surface reactions specify mineral catalysts. The network acknowledges that only racemic alanine is produced prebiotically; enantioselective production of L-alanine remains an open problem.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "Carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "Hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "Ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "Hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "Water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "Formate / Formic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "formaldehyde", "common_name": "Formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "Carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "Glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H3O3-", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoate", "common_name": "Pyruvate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)/p-1", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "Acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H6N2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanenitrile", "common_name": "\u03b1-Aminopropionitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6N2/c1-2(4)3-5/h2H,4H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "CH3NO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "Formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C2H5NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminoacetic acid", "common_name": "Glycine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H5NO2/c3-1-2(4)5/h1,3H2,(H,4,5)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C2HO3-", "iupac_name": "oxoacetate", "common_name": "Glyoxylate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "Alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(3)4(5)6/h2H,3H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C2H3NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetonitrile", "common_name": "Glycolonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H3NO/c3-1-2-4/h4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich fluids from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 adsorbs on the greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084) surface, which is structurally analogous to biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters. H\u2082 dissociates on the mineral surface providing hydride equivalents. CO\u2082 is reduced via a two-electron transfer to yield formate (HCOO\u207b). The greigite surface stabilizes the transition state and lowers the activation energy for CO\u2082 reduction.", "reasoning": "The reduction of CO\u2082 to formate on greigite under hydrothermal conditions has been experimentally demonstrated by Preiner et al. (2020) and Yamaguchi et al. (2014). Greigite's structural analogy to biological iron-sulfur clusters supports its role as a primordial catalyst for carbon fixation in alkaline hydrothermal vents. This is the first step in hydrothermal carbon fixation pathways (Sources 15641, 2546)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on mackinawite", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Requires strong reducing conditions; H\u2082 as reductant"}, "mechanism": "Formate adsorbed on mackinawite (FeS) surfaces undergoes further two-electron reduction. H\u2082 provides the reducing equivalents, with FeS mediating electron transfer. The C=O bond of formate is reduced to yield formaldehyde (CH\u2082O) and water. Mackinawite acts as an electron shuttle between H\u2082 and the substrate.", "reasoning": "Mackinawite (FeS) is a well-characterized prebiotic mineral catalyst and precursor to greigite. The stepwise reduction of formate to formaldehyde is thermodynamically feasible under hydrothermal conditions with excess H\u2082 from serpentinization (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997; Herschy et al., 2014). This step is necessary to decompose the previously oversimplified CO\u2082-to-pyruvate pathway into discrete, verifiable steps."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "450-550K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "Black smoker or high-temperature hydrothermal zone; gas-phase or supercritical conditions"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 CO + H\u2082O. On magnetite surfaces at high temperature, CO\u2082 undergoes deoxygenation. The reaction proceeds through a surface-bound carboxylate intermediate that loses one oxygen atom to form CO. Magnetite provides the redox-active iron centers that facilitate electron transfer.", "reasoning": "The reverse water-gas shift reaction (RWGS) is well established in heterogeneous catalysis and occurs on magnetite at elevated temperatures. In prebiotic contexts, this provides CO as a feedstock for Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis and carbonylation reactions (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). CO is a key intermediate in the acetyl-CoA pathway analog proposed by W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1990)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Aldol condensation of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde on pyrite", "inputs": ["mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline conditions (pH 9-11) favor aldol condensation; 2 CH\u2082O \u2192 HOCH\u2082CHO"}, "mechanism": "Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo aldol condensation on the pyrite mineral surface. The mineral surface provides Lewis acid sites that activate the carbonyl of one formaldehyde molecule, while the other formaldehyde provides the nucleophilic carbon (as an enolate-like species under alkaline conditions). The C\u2013C bond forms to produce glycolaldehyde (HOCH\u2082CHO), the simplest sugar.", "reasoning": "The dimerization of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde is the initial step of the formose reaction and is well documented under alkaline prebiotic conditions (Breslow, 1959; Ricardo et al., 2004). Mineral surfaces such as pyrite can catalyze this aldol condensation by concentrating reactants and providing catalytic sites. This reaction builds the C2 backbone needed for further chain elongation to pyruvate."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Carbonylation of glycolaldehyde to pyruvate on FeNiS minerals", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "awaruite (FeNi\u2083)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "FeNiS mineral assemblage", "aqueous": "true", "other": "CO insertion followed by rearrangement; analogous to acetyl-CoA pathway carbonylation"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde (C2) adsorbs on the FeNiS mineral surface. CO binds to a nickel center and inserts into the C\u2013H bond of glycolaldehyde, extending the carbon chain to C3. Subsequent oxidation and keto-enol tautomerization on the mineral surface yields pyruvate (CH\u2083COCOO\u207b). This is analogous to the carbonylation step in the biological Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.", "reasoning": "Cody et al. (2000) demonstrated that CO can insert into organic substrates on FeNiS surfaces under hydrothermal conditions to form higher-carbon products including pyruvate. Varma et al. (2018) showed that native iron and nickel can reduce CO\u2082 to pyruvate and other TCA cycle intermediates at 100\u00b0C. This reaction completes the stepwise decomposition of the CO\u2082-to-pyruvate pathway, avoiding the oversimplification flagged in the previous attempt."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde from CO and H\u2082", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": "false", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) conditions; CO:H\u2082 ratio ~1:2; produces C1-C3 oxygenates"}, "mechanism": "CO adsorbs dissociatively on magnetite surfaces. Hydrogen atoms from H\u2082 dissociation hydrogenate surface carbon and oxygen intermediates. Chain growth via CO insertion and subsequent hydrogenation leads to oxygenated C2 products. Acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO) is a major oxygenated product of FTT synthesis alongside methanol and ethanol.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite under hydrothermal conditions has been demonstrated by McCollom et al. (1999) and McCollom & Seewald (2006). These reactions produce a distribution of hydrocarbons and oxygenates, with acetaldehyde as a prominent product. This provides an independent route to acetaldehyde that does not require pyruvate decarboxylation, creating a convergence point at acetaldehyde."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-420K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "pyrite surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Non-oxidative decarboxylation; produces CO\u2082 as byproduct; facile at elevated temperatures"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate undergoes thermal decarboxylation, losing the carboxyl group as CO\u2082 to yield acetaldehyde. The reaction is facilitated by the electron-withdrawing \u03b1-keto group adjacent to the carboxylate. On pyrite surfaces, the mineral can act as a Lewis acid, coordinating the keto oxygen and facilitating C\u2013C bond cleavage. This is a well-known thermal decomposition of \u03b1-keto acids.", "reasoning": "The thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde and CO\u2082 is a well-established reaction that occurs readily under hydrothermal conditions (Cooper et al., 2011; Novikov & Copley, 2013). This provides a second independent route to acetaldehyde from pyruvate, creating a convergence point at mol_011 from both FTT synthesis (rxn_006) and pyruvate decarboxylation (rxn_007). The regenerated CO\u2082 can re-enter the carbon fixation cycle."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Strecker synthesis: imine formation and cyanide addition", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mildly acidic to neutral pH (4-7); acetaldehyde + NH\u2083 form imine, then HCN adds to C=N"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde condenses with ammonia to form an imine (CH\u2083CH=NH) with loss of water. HCN then attacks the electrophilic carbon of the imine via nucleophilic addition, yielding \u03b1-aminopropionitrile (CH\u2083CH(NH\u2082)CN). Montmorillonite clay concentrates the reactants on its surface and provides acid-base catalytic sites that facilitate both the imine formation and the cyanide addition steps.", "reasoning": "The Strecker reaction is one of the most established prebiotic pathways for amino acid synthesis (Strecker, 1850; Miller, 1957). It was identified as a primary mechanism in the Miller-Urey experiments (Sources 15634, 15628). The use of montmorillonite as a surface catalyst is supported by its known role in concentrating and aligning monomers for prebiotic reactions (Sources 9431). This reaction produces the racemic aminonitrile intermediate."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Hydrolysis of \u03b1-aminopropionitrile to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite; TiO\u2082 for UV-assisted hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Two-step hydrolysis: nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid; UV enhances rate; produces NH\u2083 as byproduct"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group (\u2013CN) of \u03b1-aminopropionitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis. First, water attacks the electrophilic carbon of the nitrile, producing an amide intermediate (\u03b1-aminopropanamide). Second, the amide is further hydrolyzed to the carboxylic acid, yielding alanine (CH\u2083CH(NH\u2082)COOH) and releasing NH\u2083. UV light on TiO\u2082 generates reactive hydroxyl radicals that can accelerate the hydrolysis. Montmorillonite provides the surface environment.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of aminonitriles to amino acids is the final step of the Strecker pathway and is well documented (Miller, 1957; Schlesinger & Miller, 1983 \u2014 Sources 15633, 15634). The use of TiO\u2082 as a UV photocatalyst is consistent with early Earth conditions lacking an ozone layer (Sources 15628). The released NH\u2083 recycles back into the network as a hub molecule, creating a catalytic loop."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Formamide formation from formate and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Wet-dry cycling promotes condensation; formate protonated to formic acid at surface pH; dehydration on clay surface yields formamide"}, "mechanism": "Formic acid (protonated formate at surface pH) condenses with ammonia via nucleophilic acyl substitution. The ammonia nitrogen attacks the carbonyl carbon of formic acid, displacing water to form formamide (HCONH\u2082). Montmorillonite facilitates this condensation by concentrating both reactants on its interlayer surfaces and promoting dehydration during dry phases of wet-dry cycling.", "reasoning": "The condensation of formic acid with ammonia to form formamide is part of the Cannizzaro pathway described in the literature (Sources 5960). Formamide is a key intermediate in multiple prebiotic synthesis routes. Clay mineral surfaces such as montmorillonite are well known to promote condensation reactions through wet-dry cycling (Ferris et al., 1996). Formate produced hydrothermally (rxn_001) is transported to surface environments where lower pH conditions allow protonation."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Cannizzaro pathway: formamide reacts with acetaldehyde to yield alanine", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mildly alkaline conditions (pH 8-9) favor carbamyl anion formation from formamide"}, "mechanism": "Under mildly alkaline conditions, formamide can generate a carbamyl anion (\u207bCONH\u2082), which is a strong nucleophile. This anion attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetaldehyde via nucleophilic addition. Subsequent tautomerization, protonation, and rearrangement steps yield \u03b1-aminopropanoic acid (alanine). The clay surface provides the microenvironment for this multi-step transformation.", "reasoning": "The Cannizzaro reaction pathway to alanine through formamide and acetaldehyde is described in the literature as an alternative to the Strecker route (Sources 5960). This pathway is particularly relevant to meteoritic chemistry. The mechanism proceeds via a carbamyl anion derived from formamide, which provides the amino and carboxyl functionalities. Note that acetaldehyde is required from elsewhere in the network (rxn_006 or rxn_007), addressing the previous feedback that this pathway is not self-contained."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Formose-ammonia reaction to alanine on Al-rich smectite", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["Al-rich smectite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "420K (150\u00b0C)", "pressure": "autogenous (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "Al-rich smectite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 10 (alkaline); reaction time ~31 days; 3 CH\u2082O + NH\u2083 \u2192 alanine in multi-step process"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde undergoes sequential aldol condensation and Cannizzaro disproportionation on the Al-smectite surface. The aldol steps produce glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde. These C2-C3 sugar intermediates react with ammonia through reductive amination and rearrangement pathways to produce amino acids. Specifically, dihydroxyacetone (a C3 sugar from formose chemistry) can react with ammonia to yield alanine via dehydration, reduction, and amination. Al-smectite interlayer sites concentrate reactants, catalyze the aldol steps, and provide the alkaline microenvironment. This reaction encompasses multiple substeps occurring on the mineral surface over extended timescales.", "reasoning": "This pathway is directly supported by experimental results showing that Al-rich smectites produce ~60 \u00b5M alanine after 31 days at 150\u00b0C and pH 10, significantly outperforming other mineral setups (Sources 13450, 13474, 13449, 18250). The multi-step nature of this reaction (formose chemistry + ammonia incorporation) was flagged in previous feedback. Here we acknowledge the intermediates (glycolaldehyde, dihydroxyacetone) as implicit sub-steps occurring on the mineral surface, consistent with the formose-ammonia pathway described in Sources 13498 and 10827. Fe-rich smectites inhibit this reaction (Sources 13449), highlighting the specificity of Al-rich smectite catalysis."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on FeS minerals", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "elemental iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (hydrothermal)", "catalyst": "mackinawite (FeS) and native iron (Fe\u2070)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline vent conditions; H\u2082 acts as reductant; produces racemic alanine from achiral precursors"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate reacts with ammonia to form an imine intermediate (CH\u2083C(=NH)COO\u207b). The imine is then reduced by H\u2082 activated on the FeS/Fe\u2070 mineral surface, yielding alanine. The mineral surface provides the heterogeneous catalytic sites for H\u2082 activation and hydride transfer to the C=N bond. This is the abiotic analog of the biological reductive amination catalyzed by alanine dehydrogenase.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids by ammonia is a well-established prebiotic pathway for amino acid synthesis (Sources 15293). The use of FeS and Fe\u2070 as mineral reductants is consistent with the iron-sulfur world hypothesis (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988). Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (1997) demonstrated amino acid synthesis on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces. This pathway produces racemic alanine from achiral precursors, consistent with the literature noting that prebiotic processes produce racemic mixtures (Sources 15225, 9132)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Fe\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed amination of pyruvate at moderate temperature", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K (70\u00b0C)", "pressure": "moderate", "catalyst": "dissolved Fe\u00b2\u207a from pyrite dissolution; inert atmosphere", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Inert (N\u2082) atmosphere; pH neutral to mildly alkaline; lower-temperature hydrothermal regime"}, "mechanism": "Dissolved Fe\u00b2\u207a ions (from partial dissolution of pyrite) coordinate with both pyruvate and ammonia in solution. Fe\u00b2\u207a acts as a Lewis acid, activating the keto group of pyruvate toward nucleophilic attack by ammonia. The resulting imine is reduced in situ, possibly by Fe\u00b2\u207a/Fe\u2070 redox cycling or by organic reductants. This mechanism avoids the need for gaseous H\u2082 and operates at moderate temperatures accessible in off-axis hydrothermal systems.", "reasoning": "Muchowska et al. (2019) demonstrated that Fe\u00b2\u207a catalyzes the interconversion of \u03b1-keto acids and amino acids under mild conditions (70\u00b0C, inert atmosphere), including the conversion of pyruvate to alanine (Sources 9400, 9983). This provides a lower-temperature alternative to the reductive amination in rxn_013. The off-axis, lower-temperature hydrothermal systems such as Lost City are proposed as more viable for organic synthesis than high-temperature black smokers (Sources 2626, 2627)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Transamination of pyruvate with glycine to yield alanine", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required; may be facilitated by metal ions (Cu\u00b2\u207a, Fe\u00b2\u207a)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Aqueous phosphate buffer; pH 6-8; non-enzymatic analog of biological transaminase"}, "mechanism": "Glycine transfers its amino group to the \u03b1-keto position of pyruvate through a non-enzymatic transamination reaction. The mechanism proceeds via Schiff base (aldimine/ketimine) intermediates: glycine forms a Schiff base with a metal ion or carbonyl cofactor, undergoes tautomerization to a ketimine, and transfers the nitrogen to pyruvate. This yields alanine and glyoxylate as co-products.", "reasoning": "Non-enzymatic transamination between amino acids and \u03b1-keto acids has been demonstrated under mild prebiotic conditions by Snell (1945) and Zabinski & Toney (2001) (Sources 1024, 6940). This pathway mirrors the biological synthesis of L-alanine via alanine aminotransferase and may represent an evolutionary precursor to enzymatic catalysis. This reaction requires both pyruvate (from hydrothermal pathways) and glycine (from surface Strecker synthesis), demonstrating environmental interconnection."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde, HCN, and ammonia", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite clay surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Mildly acidic to neutral pH; CH\u2082O + NH\u2083 \u2192 CH\u2082=NH \u2192 aminoacetonitrile \u2192 glycine"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde reacts with ammonia to form methyleneimine (CH\u2082=NH). HCN undergoes nucleophilic addition to the imine carbon, yielding aminoacetonitrile (H\u2082NCH\u2082CN). The aminonitrile is hydrolyzed (nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid) to produce glycine (NH\u2082CH\u2082COOH). These steps occur in one pot on the montmorillonite surface, which concentrates and aligns reactants.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis of glycine from formaldehyde, HCN, and ammonia is the simplest example of Strecker amino acid synthesis and was one of the primary products of the Miller-Urey experiment (Miller, 1953; Sources 15628, 15633, 15635). Glycine is consistently the most abundant amino acid in prebiotic synthesis experiments. Here glycine serves as a reactant for the transamination pathway (rxn_015), connecting surface and biochemical environments."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Cyanosulfidic glycolonitrile formation from formaldehyde and HCN", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083); sulfide mineral surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions; HCN adds to formaldehyde; cyanohydrin formation"}, "mechanism": "HCN undergoes nucleophilic addition to the carbonyl carbon of formaldehyde. The cyanide anion attacks the electrophilic carbon, and protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields glycolonitrile (HOCH\u2082CN), the simplest cyanohydrin. Sulfide mineral surfaces such as stibnite may facilitate this reaction by providing Lewis acid catalysis and by maintaining a local environment enriched in HCN through sulfide-mediated HCN chemistry.", "reasoning": "Glycolonitrile formation from formaldehyde and HCN is the entry point to the cyanosulfidic scenario described by Patel et al. (2015) and Sutherland (2017) (Sources 9376). This cyanohydrin is a key branch point in cyanosulfidic chemistry, leading to nucleotide precursors and amino acid precursors via different downstream pathways. The use of stibnite as a sulfide mineral catalyst is consistent with the Sutherland group's cyanosulfidic chemistry framework."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Cyanosulfidic chain extension: glycolonitrile to \u03b1-aminopropionitrile", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["stibnite (Sb\u2082S\u2083)", "molybdenite (MoS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "stibnite; molybdenite for redox catalysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions; chain extension via HCN homologation; ammonia provides amino group"}, "mechanism": "Glycolonitrile undergoes transformation on sulfide mineral surfaces. The hydroxyl group is activated (possibly via sulfide substitution or oxidation), generating an electrophilic C2 intermediate. Ammonia displaces the leaving group to form an amino-substituted C2 nitrile. Simultaneously or sequentially, HCN provides the additional carbon via a second nucleophilic addition or homologation step, extending the chain from C2 to C3 and yielding \u03b1-aminopropionitrile. The overall sequence involves reductive homologation facilitated by sulfide mineral redox chemistry.", "reasoning": "The cyanosulfidic scenario describes how simple feedstock molecules (HCN, CH\u2082O, H\u2082S) can be elaborated into complex precursors through interconnected reaction networks (Patel et al., 2015; Sources 9376). The chain extension from C2 glycolonitrile to C3 aminopropionitrile is plausible through HCN homologation chemistry. Molybdenite provides redox catalysis for the sulfide-mediated transformations. This converges on \u03b1-aminopropionitrile (mol_012), the same intermediate produced by Strecker synthesis (rxn_008), creating a convergence point."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "UV photolysis of HCN to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "280-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO\u2082 (anatase) as UV photocatalyst", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Strong UV irradiation (no ozone layer on early Earth); shallow pools or tidal flats"}, "mechanism": "HCN dissolved in water absorbs UV light (directly or via TiO\u2082 photocatalysis). UV excitation promotes the hydration of the C\u2261N triple bond. TiO\u2082 generates reactive hydroxyl radicals (\u2022OH) upon UV irradiation, which attack HCN to form an iminol intermediate (HN=CHOH). Tautomerization yields formamide (HCONH\u2082). The TiO\u2082 surface also adsorbs HCN, increasing local concentration and reaction efficiency.", "reasoning": "UV photolysis of HCN to formamide is a well-studied prebiotic reaction (Barks et al., 2010; Saladino et al., 2012; Sources 15628). Early Earth lacked an ozone layer, so intense UV radiation was available at the surface (Sources 15628). TiO\u2082 (anatase) is a known UV photocatalyst that could have been present as a mineral on early Earth. This provides a second independent route to formamide (alongside rxn_010), creating a convergence point at mol_013."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Hydrothermal CO\u2082 fixation \u2192 FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 Surface Strecker \u2192 Alanine", "description": "CO\u2082 is reduced to CO via reverse water-gas shift on magnetite in high-temperature hydrothermal zones. CO undergoes Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis to produce acetaldehyde. Acetaldehyde is transported to surface environments where it undergoes Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH\u2083 on montmorillonite to form \u03b1-aminopropionitrile, which hydrolyzes to alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal stepwise CO\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 Reductive amination \u2192 Alanine", "description": "CO\u2082 is reduced stepwise through formate and formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces. Glycolaldehyde undergoes carbonylation with CO on FeNiS to form pyruvate. Pyruvate then reacts with NH\u2083 and H\u2082 via reductive amination on FeS minerals to produce alanine directly in the hydrothermal environment.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_008", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate \u2192 Fe\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed amination \u2192 Alanine", "description": "Pyruvate formed via the hydrothermal C1 chain extension pathway (CO\u2082 \u2192 formate \u2192 formaldehyde \u2192 glycolaldehyde \u2192 pyruvate) undergoes Fe\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed amination with ammonia at moderate temperature (70\u00b0C) in off-axis hydrothermal systems, yielding alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate decarboxylation \u2192 Surface Strecker \u2192 Alanine", "description": "Pyruvate from hydrothermal synthesis undergoes thermal decarboxylation on pyrite to yield acetaldehyde. This acetaldehyde is then utilized in the surface Strecker pathway with HCN and NH\u2083 on montmorillonite to produce \u03b1-aminopropionitrile, which hydrolyzes to alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Cannizzaro pathway: formate + NH\u2083 \u2192 formamide \u2192 Alanine", "description": "Formate from hydrothermal CO\u2082 reduction is transported to surface pools where it condenses with ammonia to form formamide on montmorillonite. Formamide then reacts with acetaldehyde (from FTT or pyruvate decarboxylation) via the carbamyl anion mechanism to yield alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_010", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_013", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "UV photolysis: HCN \u2192 formamide \u2192 Alanine", "description": "HCN dissolved in surface pools undergoes UV-driven hydration on TiO\u2082 surfaces to produce formamide. This formamide reacts with acetaldehyde (from hydrothermal pathways) via the Cannizzaro mechanism to produce alanine. This pathway relies on early Earth's intense UV radiation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_019", "rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_013", "mol_011"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Formose-ammonia pathway on Al-rich smectite \u2192 Alanine", "description": "Formaldehyde from hydrothermal formate reduction undergoes the formose-ammonia reaction on Al-rich smectite at 150\u00b0C and pH 10. The multi-step reaction produces sugars (glycolaldehyde, dihydroxyacetone) that react with ammonia to form alanine directly on the mineral surface. This pathway yielded ~60 \u00b5M alanine experimentally.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_007"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Cyanosulfidic: HCN + CH\u2082O \u2192 glycolonitrile \u2192 \u03b1-aminopropionitrile \u2192 Alanine", "description": "Formaldehyde and HCN form glycolonitrile on sulfide mineral surfaces. Glycolonitrile undergoes chain extension via HCN homologation and amination to yield \u03b1-aminopropionitrile. This converges with the Strecker pathway at the aminonitrile intermediate, which hydrolyzes to alanine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_017", "rxn_018", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_017", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Biochemical transamination: glycine + pyruvate \u2192 Alanine", "description": "Glycine from surface Strecker synthesis and pyruvate from hydrothermal carbon fixation undergo non-enzymatic transamination in prebiotic pools. This mirrors the biological alanine aminotransferase reaction and produces alanine with glyoxylate as a co-product, demonstrating environmental interconnection across all three domains.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_016", "rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_015"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_014", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Cannizzaro pathway with pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde", "description": "A variant of the Cannizzaro pathway where acetaldehyde is derived from thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate (rather than FTT synthesis). Formamide from UV photolysis of HCN reacts with this pyruvate-derived acetaldehyde to yield alanine, combining hydrothermal carbon fixation with surface photochemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_019", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_010", "mol_011"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_007", "description": "Formaldehyde is the central C1 building block produced hydrothermally and consumed across environments", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004", "rxn_012", "rxn_016", "rxn_017"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "description": "Pyruvate is the key C3 \u03b1-keto acid hub connecting hydrothermal carbon fixation to multiple amination routes", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "description": "Acetaldehyde is produced by two independent routes (FTT and pyruvate decarboxylation) and consumed in Strecker and Cannizzaro pathways", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_011"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "description": "\u03b1-Aminopropionitrile is the convergence point for Strecker and cyanosulfidic routes", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_018"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_013", "description": "Formamide is produced by two independent routes (formate condensation and UV photolysis) and feeds the Cannizzaro pathway", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_019"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_011"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 506027.58383750916, "success": true, "error_message": null}
