k\": \"Longest Strecker pathway but chemically coherent. Pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde (rxn_007) is thermodynamically favorable and well-documented. The pathway then feeds into the established Strecker route. The 8-step length is a concern for prebiotic plausibility due to cumulative yield losses, but each individual step is sound. Good demonstration of hydrothermal-to-surface environmental transition.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Address cumulative yield concerns for 8-step pathway\", \"Consider whether this long pathway adds value beyond P1\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.68\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.73,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.76,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.75,\n      \"feedback\": \"Cannizzaro pathway is referenced in meteoritic chemistry literature (Source 5960) but the specific mechanism of rxn_011 (formamide + acetaldehyde \u2192 alanine) is less experimentally validated than Strecker or reductive amination routes. The formation of carbamyl anion from formamide and its reaction with acetaldehyde to directly produce alanine requires more detailed mechanistic justification. The formate-to-formamide step (rxn_010) is also somewhat underspecified\u2014what surface mineral catalyzes this?\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Provide detailed mechanism for rxn_011 including intermediates\", \"Specify mineral catalyst for rxn_010 surface reaction\", \"Include experimental yield data for Cannizzaro pathway to alanine\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_019\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.68\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.73,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.74,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.78,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.74,\n      \"feedback\": \"Short pathway but relies on the same problematic rxn_011 as P5. UV photolysis of HCN to formamide (rxn_019) is supported\u2014HCN hydration under UV is documented. However, the pathway does not specify how acetaldehyde is obtained for rxn_011, making it incomplete as described. The Cannizzaro final step remains the weak link.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Explicitly include acetaldehyde source in pathway\", \"Consider alternative formamide-to-alanine mechanisms\", \"Add mineral specification for UV photolysis environment\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.82\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.83,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.82,\n      \"feedback\": \"Strongly supported by Al-rich smectite literature (Sources 13450, 13474) showing ~60 \u00b5M alanine after 31 days at 150\u00b0C. However, rxn_012 oversimplifies what is actually a complex formose-type chemistry: going from formaldehyde (C1) + NH\u2083 to alanine (C3) in one step implies multiple formaldehyde condensation, isomerization, and amination sub-steps. The net reaction is experimentally validated but mechanistically opaque. The pathway is short and efficient, making it attractive.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Decompose rxn_012 into sub-steps showing C1\u2192C2\u2192C3 chain building\", \"Specify that multiple equivalents of formaldehyde are consumed\", \"Note that the mechanism likely involves formose intermediates like glycolaldehyde and dihydroxyacetone\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.90\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.83,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.84,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.87,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n      \"feedback\": \"Well-aligned with Patel et al. cyanosulfidic scenario (Source 9376). Glycolonitrile formation from formaldehyde + HCN (rxn_017) is a standard cyanohydrin reaction. The chain extension step (rxn_018) from glycolonitrile to \u03b1-aminopropionitrile is plausible but the specific mechanism\u2014does it involve HCN addition to an imine intermediate?\u2014needs clarification. Convergence at \u03b1-aminopropionitrile with P1/P4 is a nice network feature. Final hydrolysis is standard.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Detail the mechanism of rxn_018: is it imine formation then HCN addition?\", \"Specify whether sulfide species play a role in the cyanosulfidic chain extension\", \"Include experimental evidence for glycolonitrile-to-aminopropionitrile conversion\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.78,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.83\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.83,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n      \"feedback\": \"Excellent demonstration of Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface \u2192 Biochemical environmental flow. Glycine synthesis via Strecker (rxn_016) is textbook. Transamination 